#Adding an Item#

-STEP 1- Add the item to Item.java.

IRON("Iron", "items/iron.png", true, 50, null)


#Adding a Tool#

-STEP 1- Add a new entry to the ItemClass enum in ItemClass.java if the tool class does not already exist.

-STEP 2- Add the item to Item.java, referencing the tool class.

IRON_AXE("Iron Axe", "items/iron_axe.png", false, 1, ItemClass.AXE)


#Adding a WorldObject#

-STEP 1- Add the type to the enum in WorldObject.java.

public enum Type { TREE, ROCK, BUSH, GRASS, CAMPFIRE, PALMTREE, SEASHELLS, RUBBLE, IRON_ORE }

-STEP 2- Register its sprite config in ObjectSpriteCache.java.

CONFIGS.put(WorldObject.Type.IRON_ORE, new SpriteConfig(
    "spritesheets/iron_ore.png",
    4, 4,                        // cols, rows in spritesheet
    SelectionMode.RANDOM,        // FIXED, RANDOM, or ANIMATED
    0,                           // fixedIndex (ignored for RANDOM)
    16, 16,                      // draw width, height (in 16px units)
    0, 0,                        // offset X, Y
    0f,                          // animFps (0 = not animated)
    12, 8, 2, 0                  // hitbox W, H, offX, offY (omit if no collider)
));

-STEP 3- Define how it is harvested in HarvestRegistry.java.

REGISTRY.put(WorldObject.Type.IRON_ORE,
    new HarvestDefinition(ItemClass.PICKAXE, 10,
        new DropTable().addDrop(Item.IRON, 2, 5, 1.0f)));

-STEP 4- Make it spawn in the world in ChunkLoader.java.

if (terrain.equals("mountain") && rng.nextFloat() < 0.08f) {
    objType = WorldObject.Type.IRON_ORE;
}


#Adding a Placed Object#

All placed objects — walls, machines, animated objects, lights — go through PlacedObjectCache using the unified SpriteConfig and RenderMode system. There is no longer any split between tiled objects and animated/delegating objects. Every type is configured in one place.

-STEP 1- Add the type to the enum in PlacedObject.java.

public enum Type { WOOD_WALL, STONE_WALL }

-STEP 2- Register its sprite config in PlacedObjectCache.java. Choose the RenderMode that matches the sprite behaviour.

For an auto-tiling wall use RenderMode.WALL. The rows parameter can be set to 0 to auto-detect from the texture height.

CONFIGS.put(PlacedObject.Type.STONE_WALL,
    new SpriteConfig(
        "tileset/Wall/stone.png", 3, 0,
        RenderMode.WALL, 0,
        16f, 16f, 0f, 0f,
        16, 16, 0, 0,
        true));   // true = solid (blocks movement)

For a static single-frame object use RenderMode.FIXED.

CONFIGS.put(PlacedObject.Type.SOME_MACHINE,
    new SpriteConfig(
        "machines/model/some_machine.png", 1, 1,
        RenderMode.FIXED, 0,
        16f, 16f, 0f, 0f,
        12, 10, 2, 0,
        true));

For an animated object use RenderMode.ANIMATED and supply animFps.

CONFIGS.put(PlacedObject.Type.SOME_LIGHT,
    new SpriteConfig(
        "spritesheets/some_light.png", 4, 1,
        RenderMode.ANIMATED, 0,
        16f, 16f, 0f, 0f,
        8f,              // animation frames per second
        12, 8, 2, 0,
        false));

For a decorative object with random sprite variants use RenderMode.RANDOM.

CONFIGS.put(PlacedObject.Type.SOME_DECO,
    new SpriteConfig(
        "spritesheets/some_deco.png", 4, 4,
        RenderMode.RANDOM, 0,
        16f, 16f, 0f, 0f,
        false));   // no hitbox, not solid

-STEP 3- Bind an item to the placed type in PlaceableRegistry.java.

REGISTRY.put(Item.STONE,
    new PlaceableDefinition(PlacedObject.Type.STONE_WALL, 1));

The second argument is the item cost per placement. To restrict placement to specific terrain types pass them as extra arguments.

new PlaceableDefinition(PlacedObject.Type.STONE_WALL, 1, "grass", "forest")

-STEP 4- Define how it is removed in PlacedHarvestRegistry.java.

REGISTRY.put(PlacedObject.Type.STONE_WALL,
    new HarvestDefinition(ItemClass.PICKAXE, 5,
        new DropTable().addDrop(Item.STONE, 1, 1, 1.0f)));

If the object should emit light (like a lantern or campfire), make sure the type is handled in the attachLight method in PlacedObject.java so a light source is created when the object is placed and destroyed when it is removed.


#Adding a Floor#

Floors are a special category of placed object. They draw on the lowest rendering layer — always below pipes and every other placed object — and other non-floor objects can be placed on top of them. Hitting a tile that has both a floor and an object on top will always target the object first; the floor only becomes the hit target once the tile is clear. Four files need to be edited.

-STEP 1- Add the type to the enum in PlacedObject.java, then add it to the isFloor() method in the same file.

public enum Type { ..., SLATE_FLOOR }

public boolean isFloor() { return type == Type.WOOD_FLOOR || type == Type.STONE_FLOOR || type == Type.SLATE_FLOOR; }

-STEP 2- Register its sprite config in PlacedObjectCache.java. Floors use RenderMode.WALL for auto-tiling and take a trailing true as their final constructor argument to mark them as floor-layer objects. They have no hitbox and are not solid.

CONFIGS.put(PlacedObject.Type.SLATE_FLOOR,
    new SpriteConfig(
        "tileset/Floor/slate_floor.png", 3, 0,
        RenderMode.WALL, 0,
        16f, 16f, 0f, 0f,
        0f, 0, 0, 0, 0,
        false, 1, 1,
        true));   // true = treat as floor layer

The spritesheet layout is the same 3-column WALL auto-tile sheet used by walls and pipes.

-STEP 3- Bind an item to the placed type in PlaceableRegistry.java.

REGISTRY.put(Item.SLATE,
    new PlaceableDefinition(PlacedObject.Type.SLATE_FLOOR, 1));

-STEP 4- Define how it is removed in PlacedHarvestRegistry.java.

REGISTRY.put(PlacedObject.Type.SLATE_FLOOR,
    new HarvestDefinition(ItemClass.PICKAXE, 3,
        new DropTable().addDrop(Item.SLATE, 1, 1, 1.0f)));

AUTO-TILING NOTE:
All floor types auto-tile with each other regardless of their specific type. The isSameType() check in PlacedObject treats any two floor types as neighbours, so WOOD_FLOOR, STONE_FLOOR, and any new floor you add will connect seamlessly at their edges.


#Adding a Pipe#

Pipes are placed objects stored in a dedicated pipeLookup rather than placedObjectLookup. They are only visible when the player holds a pipe item (PIPES_VISIBLE) or, for item pipes, a wrench (ITEM_PIPES_VISIBLE). They auto-tile using the WALL render mode and are never solid. Four files need to be edited for a basic liquid-carrying pipe.

-STEP 1- Add the type to the enum in PlacedObject.java, then add it to the isPipe() method in the same file.

public enum Type { ..., REINFORCED_PIPE }

public boolean isPipe() { return type == Type.BASIC_PIPE || type == Type.FILTER_PIPE || type == Type.ITEM_PIPE || type == Type.REINFORCED_PIPE; }

-STEP 2- Register its sprite config in PlacedObjectCache.java. Pipes use RenderMode.WALL and are not solid — pass false as the solid argument and omit the hitbox values.

CONFIGS.put(PlacedObject.Type.REINFORCED_PIPE,
    new SpriteConfig(
        "tileset/Pipe/reinforced_pipe.png", 3, 0,
        RenderMode.WALL, 0,
        16f, 16f, 0f, 0f,
        false));   // not solid, no hitbox

-STEP 3- Bind an item to the placed type in PlaceableRegistry.java.

REGISTRY.put(Item.REINFORCED_PIPE,
    new PlaceableDefinition(PlacedObject.Type.REINFORCED_PIPE, 1));

-STEP 4- Define how it is removed in PlacedHarvestRegistry.java.

REGISTRY.put(PlacedObject.Type.REINFORCED_PIPE,
    new HarvestDefinition(ItemClass.WRENCH, 1,
        new DropTable().addDrop(Item.REINFORCED_PIPE, 1, 1, 1.0f)));

VISIBILITY:
The player must be holding a pipe item for liquid pipes to appear. isHoldingPipe() in InteractionHandler checks the equipped item against the pipe item types. If your new pipe should only be visible alongside existing pipe types, add its item to that check. If it should have different visibility rules (e.g. always visible, or visible when holding a specific tool), add a separate boolean flag on PlacedObject in the same style as PIPES_VISIBLE and ITEM_PIPES_VISIBLE.

LIQUID TRANSPORT:
A basic pipe added here will automatically participate in the liquid pipe network. LiquidManager connects machines to pipes by adjacency — no extra wiring is needed.

SPECIAL PIPE BEHAVIOUR:
If the pipe needs per-pipe configuration (like FILTER_PIPE restricting liquid types) you will need to add a dedicated UI class, a findNearby method in WorldManager, a configuration record in WorldDelta, and handling in InteractionHandler. Follow the pattern established by FilterPipeUI, findNearbyFilterPipe(), and the related WorldDelta fields.

For item transport pipes specifically, see the Item Transport section at the bottom of this document.


#Adding a Crafting Recipe#

Only one file needs to be edited: CraftingManager.java.

-STEP 1- Add the recipe to the static recipes block. For a simple single-ingredient recipe:

recipes.add(new CraftingRecipe("Stone Wall", Item.STONE_WALL, 4)
    .addInput(Item.STONE, 2));

For a multi-ingredient recipe:

recipes.add(new CraftingRecipe("Iron Axe", Item.IRON_AXE, 1)
    .addInput(Item.STICK, 5)
    .addInput(Item.IRON,  8));


#Adding a Sifting Recipe#

Only one file needs to be edited: CraftingManager.java.

-STEP 1- Add the recipe to the static siftRecipes block. The first argument is the display name, the second is the input item. Each addOutput call registers a possible result with a weighted chance.

siftRecipes.add(new SiftingRecipe("Sand", Item.SAND)
    .addOutput(Item.SCRAP,    85)
    .addOutput(Item.SEASHELL, 10)
    .addOutput(Item.GEMSTONE,  5));

The weights do not need to sum to 100. They are relative — a weight of 85 out of a total of 100 means an 85% chance. You can use any integers you like; the recipe rolls a random number against the total weight to pick a result.


#Adding a Crushing Recipe#

Only one file needs to be edited: CraftingManager.java.

-STEP 1- Add the recipe to the static crushRecipes block. Each recipe takes one input item and produces one output item in a fixed quantity.

crushRecipes.add(new CrushingRecipe(
    "Crushed Iron", Item.RAW_IRON, Item.CRUSHED_IRON, 2));

The four arguments are: display name, input item, output item, output quantity.


#Adding a Smelting Recipe#

Smelting converts a crushed ore item into a molten liquid that is deposited directly into the Furnace's tank. Two files need to be edited.

-STEP 1- Add the liquid type to LiquidType.java (see the Adding a Liquid section below if you have not done this yet).

-STEP 2- Add the recipe to the static smeltRecipes block in CraftingManager.java. The arguments are: display name, input item, output liquid type, and how many units are deposited into the furnace tank on a successful smelt.

smeltRecipes.add(new SmeltingRecipe(
    "Smelt Iron", Item.CRUSHED_IRON, LiquidType.MOLTEN_IRON, 50f));


#Adding a Fishing Recipe#

A fishing recipe defines the weighted drop table for a given rod item. Fishing consumes no items — a failed minigame simply yields nothing. Only one file needs to be edited: CraftingManager.java.

-STEP 1- Add the recipe to the static fishRecipes block. The argument is the rod Item. Each addOutput call registers a possible catch with a weighted chance. Use setDifficulty() to assign a minigame difficulty (SIMPLE, MEDIUM, or COMPLEX).

fishRecipes.add(new FishingRecipe(Item.IRON_ROD)
    .setDifficulty(FishingMinigame.Difficulty.MEDIUM)
    .addOutput(Item.FISH,          60)
    .addOutput(Item.SEASHELL,      25)
    .addOutput(Item.GEMSTONE,      15));

The weights work identically to sifting — they are relative and do not need to sum to 100. If setDifficulty() is not called, the recipe defaults to MEDIUM.

To add a new rod type with its own drop table:

-STEP 1- Add an ItemClass.FISHING_ROD entry to ItemClass.java if the class does not already exist (it does by default).

-STEP 2- Add the rod item to Item.java with ItemClass.FISHING_ROD as its tool class.

IRON_ROD("Iron Rod", "items/iron_rod.png", false, 1, ItemClass.FISHING_ROD)

-STEP 3- Add a crafting recipe for the rod in CraftingManager.java (optional).

-STEP 4- Add a fishing recipe for the rod in the static fishRecipes block in CraftingManager.java (see above).

That is all that is required. isHoldingFishingRod() in InteractionHandler detects any item whose tool class is FISHING_ROD, so new rods are picked up automatically.


#Adding a Soldering Recipe#

The Soldering Table crafts electronic components from multiple input items. Only one file needs to be edited: CraftingManager.java.

-STEP 1- Add the recipe to the static solderingRecipes block. The constructor takes a display name, output item, and output quantity. Each addInput call registers a required ingredient.

solderingRecipes.add(new SolderingRecipe("Circuit Board", Item.CIRCUIT_BOARD, 1)
    .addInput(Item.EMPTY_CIRCUIT_BOARD, 1)
    .addInput(Item.CAPACITOR,           1)
    .addInput(Item.RESISTOR,            1)
    .addInput(Item.MICROCHIP,           1));

Multiple addInput calls for the same item are merged (quantities are summed). The recipe checks and removes all inputs atomically — if any ingredient is missing nothing is consumed.


#Adding a Planter Recipe#

A planter recipe defines what a seed item grows into inside a PLANTER machine. The planter requires a water supply piped in; fertilizer is optional but speeds growth by 1.5×. Three files need to be edited.

-STEP 1- Add the seed item to Item.java if it does not already exist (see Adding an Item).

-STEP 2- Add the recipe to the static planterRecipes block in CraftingManager.java. The constructor takes a display name, the seed item, the grow duration in seconds, and the water consumption rate in units per second. Each addDrop call registers a weighted output with a quantity range.

planterRecipes.add(new PlanterRecipe("Quale Seeds", Item.QUALE_SEEDS, 60f, 0.5f)
    .addDrop(Item.QUALE_SEEDS,  70, 1, 3)   // weight, minQty, maxQty
    .addDrop(Item.WOOD,         20, 1, 2)
    .addDrop(Item.LEAF,         10, 5, 10)
    .setGrowSheet("machines/farming/quale_plant.png"));

Use the three-argument addDrop overload if min and max are the same:

    .addDrop(Item.WOOD, 20, 2)   // always drops exactly 2

setGrowSheet points to a 9-frame horizontal spritesheet used to animate the plant as it grows (frames 0–8, left to right). The planter automatically advances through frames based on grow progress.

-STEP 3- Ensure the seed item can be planted via the planter's UI. getPlanterRecipeFor() in CraftingManager is called at plant time; as long as the recipe is registered in the planterRecipes list it will be found automatically. No further wiring is needed.

HOW IT WORKS:
  - The planter ticks every game update. It withdraws water (and optionally fertilizer) from
    its input tanks each tick.
  - If insufficient water is available (< 1% of the required amount) the grow timer pauses.
  - With fertilizer present the timer advances at FERTILIZER_SPEED_MULT (1.5×) speed.
  - When the timer reaches growDuration a drop is rolled and placed into the planter's
    internal 9-slot inventory first. If that is full the item is pushed to an adjacent
    ITEM_PIPE, then to an adjacent STORAGE_CRATE, and finally dropped in the world.
  - The planter's state (seed, timer, frame) is stored in PlanterManager and keyed by
    tile position. Call onPlanterRemoved() when a planter is destroyed to free state.

CHANGING FERTILIZER SPEED:
  Edit FERTILIZER_SPEED_MULT in PlanterRecipe.java (currently 1.5f).


#Adding a Mixing Recipe#

The Mixer takes two or more liquid inputs and combines them into a new output liquid. All state is managed by the mixer's PlacedObject; the player selects a recipe via MixerUI. Only one file needs to be edited: MixingRecipe.java.

-STEP 1- Add the recipe to the static ALL list in MixingRecipe.java. The constructor takes a display name, the output LiquidType, the output rate in units per second, and the output tank capacity. Each addInput call registers one input liquid with its consumption rate and tank capacity.

ALL.add(new MixingRecipe("Coolant", LiquidType.COOLANT, 4f, 100f)
    .addInput(LiquidType.WATER,          6f, 80f)
    .addInput(LiquidType.MOLTEN_SNOWITE,  2f, 40f));

The arguments to addInput are: liquid type, units consumed per second, and the capacity of that input tank on the mixer.

-STEP 2- Make sure both input and output LiquidTypes exist in LiquidType.java (see Adding a Liquid). If the output is a new liquid you will need to add it there first.

HOW IT WORKS:
  - The mixer creates one input LiquidTank per InputSpec and one output LiquidTank when a
    recipe is selected. Tanks are sized to the capacities defined in the recipe.
  - Each game tick the mixer checks whether all input tanks have liquid. If so it withdraws
    the ratePerSecond amounts from each input and deposits outputRate units into the output.
  - The output tank behaves as a PRODUCER in the pipe network and will push its liquid into
    any connected pipe automatically via LiquidManager.
  - The player opens MixerUI by interacting with a placed MIXER. Clicking a recipe row
    selects it (or deselects if already active). The UI shows live fill-bar status for every
    tank of the active recipe.
  - Recipe order in ALL determines display order in the UI.


#Adding a Liquid#

A liquid is just an entry in the LiquidType enum. Everything else — the pipe system, tanks, UI — picks it up automatically.

-STEP 1- Add the entry to LiquidType.java. Supply a display name and a libGDX Color (RGBA, each channel 0.0–1.0). The color is used for the in-world liquid fill rendering and any debug overlays.

MOLTEN_IRON("Molten Iron", new Color(0.80f, 0.35f, 0.05f, 0.95f)),

-STEP 2- If the liquid should be castable into an ingot, add a case for it in the toIngot() method in LiquidType.java.

case MOLTEN_IRON: return Item.IRON_INGOT;

That is all that is required to define a new liquid. You can then reference it in smelting recipes, machine definitions, or anywhere else that takes a LiquidType.


#Adding a Liquid Machine#

A liquid machine is any placed object that produces, stores, or consumes liquid. The pipe system connects machines automatically based on adjacency. Four files need to be edited.

-STEP 1- Add the type to the enum in PlacedObject.java.

public enum Type { ..., OIL_PUMP }

-STEP 2- Register its sprite config in PlacedObjectCache.java (see Adding a Placed Object for the full SpriteConfig reference).

CONFIGS.put(PlacedObject.Type.OIL_PUMP,
    new SpriteConfig(
        "machines/model/oil_pump.png", 1, 1,
        RenderMode.FIXED, 0,
        16f, 20f, 0f, 0f,
        16, 10, 0, 0,
        true));

-STEP 3- Bind an item to the placed type in PlaceableRegistry.java and define removal in PlacedHarvestRegistry.java (same as a normal placed object).

-STEP 4- Add ONE entry to LiquidMachineRegistry.java using the appropriate convenience factory.

For a PRODUCER (generates liquid over time, e.g. a well or pump):

REGISTRY.put(PlacedObject.Type.OIL_PUMP,
    LiquidMachineDefinition.producer(80f, LiquidType.OIL, 2f));

The three arguments are: tank capacity in units, the liquid type produced, and units generated per second.

For a STORAGE machine (passively holds whatever liquid flows in, e.g. a barrel or tank):

REGISTRY.put(PlacedObject.Type.LARGE_TANK,
    LiquidMachineDefinition.storage(500f));

The single argument is the tank capacity in units.

For a RECEIVER (actively consumes liquid, e.g. a boiler or still):

REGISTRY.put(PlacedObject.Type.BOILER,
    LiquidMachineDefinition.receiver(60f, LiquidType.WATER, 2f));

The three arguments are: tank capacity in units, the liquid type it accepts (null to accept any), and units consumed per second.

If the machine needs custom behaviour — for example, the Furnace which is a producer but is filled manually by a minigame rather than automatically — use the full constructor instead of a factory:

REGISTRY.put(PlacedObject.Type.FURNACE,
    new LiquidMachineDefinition(
        LiquidTank.Role.PRODUCER, 100f,
        null, 0f,   // no auto-production; filled manually via tank.deposit()
        null, 0f));

Once the registry entry exists, PlacedObject's constructor creates the LiquidTank automatically and the LiquidManager will include the machine in pipe-network flow on every update tick. No further wiring is needed.


#Adding a Cast Recipe#

The Cast machine accepts molten liquid piped into it and produces a solid ingot after a 30-second process. To support a new ore through the cast, two files need to be edited.

-STEP 1- Make sure the liquid type exists in LiquidType.java (see Adding a Liquid above).

-STEP 2- Add a case for the new liquid in the toIngot() method in LiquidType.java, mapping it to the ingot item it should produce.

case MOLTEN_IRON: return Item.IRON_INGOT;

That is all that is needed. The cast will automatically accept any liquid whose toIngot() returns a non-null item, process it once the tank reaches full capacity, and drop the ingot at the cast's location when the timer completes.

To change how much liquid is required per ingot, adjust the capacity value in LiquidMachineRegistry.java:

REGISTRY.put(PlacedObject.Type.CAST,
    LiquidMachineDefinition.receiver(50f, null, 0f));  // 50f = units required per ingot

To change the casting animation frame order or phase durations, edit getCastFrameIndex() in PlacedObject.java. The 2x2 spritesheet is indexed as follows:

    0 = top-left     (empty / idle)
    1 = top-right    (hot)
    2 = bottom-left  (less hot)
    3 = bottom-right (medium)

The cast will not accept water or any liquid whose toIngot() returns null.

-STEP 3-
LiquidMachineDefinition def = LiquidMachineRegistry.get(type); In PlacedObject

#Item Transport (Item Pipes)#

Item pipes move items between storage crates automatically. Three classes handle the system:
  ItemPipeConfig.java   — per-pipe port settings (DISABLED / INPUT / OUTPUT per side)
  ItemPipeNetwork.java  — tick-based simulation that moves items along connected pipes
  ItemPipeUI.java       — wrench configuration overlay

The ITEM_PIPE placed-object type already exists in PlacedObject.Type. The pipe is placed and
removed through the standard pipe lookup (world.getPipeLookup()), just like BASIC_PIPE.

HOW IT WORKS FOR THE PLAYER:
  1. Place ITEM_PIPE tiles between two storage crates.
  2. Hold WRENCH_AND_SCREW and press E near any ITEM_PIPE.
  3. A 4-button overlay appears. Each button represents one cardinal direction.
     Click a button to cycle: OFF → IN → OUT → OFF ...
     Blue (IN)  = this side pulls items from the adjacent crate into the pipe.
     Orange (OUT) = this side pushes items from the pipe into the adjacent crate.
  4. Items move every 0.5 seconds. One item is transferred per tick per pipe.

ADDING A NEW MACHINE TYPE AS A SOURCE/DESTINATION:
  In ItemPipeNetwork.getCrateInventory(), add an extra type check alongside the existing
  STORAGE_CRATE checks, and ensure the machine has an entry in the crateInventories map
  (or supply a different inventory accessor). No other changes are required.

CHANGING TICK SPEED:
  Edit the TICK_INTERVAL constant in ItemPipeNetwork.java (seconds between ticks).

SAVE/LOAD:
  ItemPipeConfig is encoded as a single int (2 bits per direction × 4 = 8 bits).
  WorldDelta stores it in PlacedRecord.itemPipeConfigBits and persists it like any other
  field. Bump MAGIC in WorldDelta if you change the binary layout.

EXTENDING THE CONFIG (e.g. filter by item type):
  Add fields to ItemPipeConfig, add a new PortMode if needed, update encode()/decode(),
  add a new update*/get* pair in WorldDelta, and extend the ItemPipeUI buttons.
